    <article class="container mx-auto text-center bg-white rounded-xl p-2 my-4 shadow-lg md:px-20 md:my-10">
      <h1 class="md:text-4xl text-2xl font-bold">Self confidence</h1>
      <p class="md:text-1xl text-sm inline-block mx-1 my-5">Written by</p>
      <p class="md:text-base text-sm inline-block text-blue-600">Rico</p>
      <div class="flex-row flex justify-center">
        <img src="https://th.bing.com/th/id/OIP.kWJIwO8N46uendHPJeB_SwHaFI?w=277&h=192&c=7&r=0&o=5&dpr=1.3&pid=1.7"
          alt="Card img" class="object-cover object-center w-1/2" />
      </div>
      <div class="md:mx-10 mx-5 my-10 text-justify">
        <p>
          Self-confidence is a part of personality development that involves
          trusting in your own abilities, judgment, and capacities. It’s about
          feeling worthy and valuing yourself, regardless of what others think
          or any imperfections you may have.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Self-confident people seem at ease with themselves and their work.
          They invite trust and inspire confidence in others. These are all
          attractive characteristics to have.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          But it’s not always easy to be confident in yourself, particularly if
          you’re naturally self-critical or if other people put you down.
          Thankfully, there are steps you can take to increase and maintain your
          self-confidence.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          In here, we going to explain what self-confidence is and why it
          matters. We'll explore how to believe in yourself and how to project
          this belief to others, so that you can be more effective and happier
          in your life and work.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mt-5">
          What Is Self-Confidence – and Why Is It Important?
        </h3>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Having self-confidence entails having faith in your own abilities,
          judgment, and capabilities. It's about feeling worthy and appreciating
          who you are, in spite of your flaws or what other people may think of
          you.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Confidence is frequently confused with self-efficacy and self-esteem.
          Nonetheless, they differ slightly. When we observe ourselves winning
          tasks and reaching objectives, we feel more capable of achieving our
          own goals. This gives us hope that we can succeed if we put a lot of
          effort and learning into a certain field. People who possess this kind
          of confidence are able to rise to challenging situations and persevere
          in the face of failure.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Self-esteem is a broader perception that we are capable of handling
          life's challenges and that we have the right to be content.
          Furthermore, part of what makes us feel good about ourselves is the
          belief that those around us share our views. We may or may not be able
          to manage this, and if we receive a lot of negative feedback or
          rejection from people, our self-worth may quickly decline until we
          find other sources of encouragement.
        </p>
        <table class="border-collapse border border-gray-500 mt-2 sm:mt-2 mx-auto sm:rounded-lg">
          <thead>
            <tr class="bg-gray-500 text-white">
              <th class="py-2 px-4 text-left">Confident Behavior</th>
              <th class="py-2 px-4 text-left">
                Behavior Associated With Low Self-Confidence
              </th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="bg-white border-b border-gray-500">
              <td class="py-2 px-4">
                Following your moral convictions even in the face of mockery or
                criticism from others.
              </td>
              <td class="py-2 px-4">
                Controlling your actions according to the opinions of others.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-white border-b border-gray-500">
              <td class="py-2 px-4">
                Being prepared to take chances and go above and beyond to
                accomplish greater results.
              </td>
              <td class="py-2 px-4">
                Avoiding risk, being afraid of failing, and remaining in your
                comfort zone.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-white border-b border-gray-500">
              <td class="py-2 px-4">
                Recognizing your mistakes and growing from them.
              </td>
              <td class="py-2 px-4">
                Putting a lot of effort into hiding errors and praying you can
                address the issue before anyone notices.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-white border-b border-gray-500">
              <td class="py-2 px-4">
                Waiting for compliments from others on your achievements.
              </td>
              <td class="py-2 px-4">
                Praying for yourself and your qualities to as many people as you
                can.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-white border-b border-gray-500">
              <td class="py-2 px-4">
                Accepting praises politely. "Thank you; I put a lot of effort
                into that prospectus. I'm glad my efforts are acknowledged."
              </td>
              <td class="py-2 px-4">
                Blithely brushing off praises. "Oh, frankly, that prospectus
                wasn't that important. It might have been done by anyone."
              </td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p class="mt-3">
          As we can see self-confident people are generally more positive – they
          value themselves and trust their judgment. But they also acknowledge
          their failures and mistakes, and learn from them. As low
          self-confidence can be self-destructive, and may manifest itself as
          negativity.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mt-5">Why Self-Confidence Matters</h3>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Despite the fact that self-confidence is essential in practically
          every area of our life, many people lack it. Unfortunately, this can
          spiral out of control: those who lack confidence are less likely to
          succeed in life and gain the confidence that would boost their
          self-esteem.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          For instance, you might not be inclined to support a project that is
          proposed by someone who appears unsure of himself, makes mistakes, or
          apologizes a lot. Conversely, you are convinced by someone who answers
          questions confidently, talks clearly, and holds their head up.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Others are inspired to be confident by self-assured individuals,
          including their friends, supervisors, coworkers, and audience. And one
          of the most important strategies for success is to win other people's
          trust. We'll look at how you can accomplish this in the sections that
          follow.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mt-5">
          How to Appear More Confident to Others
        </h3>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Picture anyone you know that you think of as highly confident – what
          characteristics do they have that make you think this? It's most
          likely one or more of these things:
        </p>
        <ol class="mt-5 list-decimal font-semibold">
          <li class="mx-10 mb-2">
            The way they speak (tone, how they project their voice, words)
          </li>
          <li class="mx-10 mb-2">Their energy and enthusiasm</li>
          <li class="mx-10 mb-2">
            How expert or knowledgeable they are about something
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p class="mt-3">
          You can show self-confidence in your behavior, your body language, and
          in what you say and how you say it.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Projecting a positive image to others can help you to improve your
          self-confidence. It's not simply a matter of "faking it" – if you
          project with confidence, others are more likely to respond well, and
          this positive feedback will help you to believe in yourself.
        </p>
        <ol class="mt-5 list-decimal font-semibold">
          <li class="mx-10 mb-2 text-base">Body Language</li>
          <div class="mx-10 mb-5 font-normal text-sm">
            <p class="mb-2">
              According to Amy Cuddy's book Presence: Bringing Your Boldest Self
              to Your Biggest Challenges, you may develop confidence simply by
              changing the way you move and hold yourself.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-3">
              During meetings, for example, we often shrink ourselves by
              slouching, hunching our shoulders, and lowering our heads when we
              are nervous. You can feel less worried and more forceful just by
              sitting up straight.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-3">
              Spreading your hands apart and extending your palms slightly
              toward your audience during a presentation communicates openness
              and a desire to exchange information.
            </p>
          </div>
          <li class="mx-10 mb-2">Face-to-Face Communication</li>
          <div class="mx-10 mb-5 font-normal text-sm">
            <p class="mb-2">
              Making a strong first impression is typically challenging for
              people who lack confidence, regardless of whether they are
              presenting a presentation, meeting a client, or addressing a
              meeting. Even if you might be hesitant or self-conscious, you can
              act right now to project greater confidence.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-3">
              It's crucial to interact with others, so keep your eyes open while
              you speak. This demonstrates your interest in the other person's
              point of view and your active participation in the discussion.
              While the conversation is going on, try not to fidget or look away
              as this could give the impression that you are nervous or
              distracted.
            </p>
          </div>
          <li class="mx-10 mb-2">Build Expert Power</li>
          <div class="mx-10 mb-5 font-normal text-sm">
            <p class="mb-2">
              When you are confident in your knowledge, you will probably come
              across as such. Possessing extensive knowledge about a subject can
              make you better equipped to respond to inquiries and make
              spontaneous remarks.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-3">
              If a gap in your knowledge is the reason for your lack of
              confidence, make an effort to learn more. Are there any webinars
              or events that would be of interest to you? Is there something you
              could study? Alternatively, you may look for a mentor. For more
              information on this, see our skillbook and essay, Building Expert
              Power.
            </p>
          </div>
        </ol>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mt-5">Rebuilding Confidence at Work</h3>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Many people's confidence is badly impacted by changes in their work
          environment and extended absences from it. According to one survey,
          more than one-third of workers who return to the office after a year
          or more away feel less confident in their own skills. For example, if
          you work from home, you could find it difficult to be heard in
          meetings or feel alone or confused without your coworkers.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Seeking to determine the root of the issue is the first step in
          addressing confidence declines. It makes sense to develop your skills
          if you believe that there are some duties you are incapable of doing.
          Do a personal SWOT analysis to determine your advantages and
          disadvantages. Create an action plan after that to focus on your
          weaker areas.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          You may not feel confident because of the attitudes or actions of
          other individuals. You may think that unfavorable assumptions about
          you are made by your coworkers. It's possible that you're experiencing
          bullying or microaggressions. If so, you should confront this conduct.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          You can let the person in charge know that their actions are
          detrimental by using the Situation-Behavior-Impact Feedback Tool.
          Consult your line manager for assistance if you don't feel comfortable
          speaking with them. Speak with a team member, HR, or, if you have one,
          your employee support network, if they are contributing to the issue.
          Bullying and prejudice at work are never acceptable under any
          circumstances.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Individuals with low self-esteem frequently believe that people can
          treat them poorly and that they don't deserve to be happy. Although
          the sensation can be genuine, the belief is definitely false!
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mt-5">
          Three Ways to Build Your Confidence
        </h3>
        <p class="mt-3">
          While there are quick fixes to address acute issues with your
          self-confidence, building confidence in the long term requires making
          some changes to your lifestyle and forming robust plans. Here are
          three ways to do that:
        </p>
        <ol class="mt-5 list-decimal font-semibold">
          <li class="mx-10 mb-2 text-base">Build Confident Habits</li>
          <div class="mx-10 mb-5 font-normal text-sm">
            <p class="mb-2">
              To enhance and elevate your self-worth, endeavor to form positive
              behaviors and severe negative ones! Your physical and emotional
              well-being can be significantly enhanced by regular exercise and a
              nutritious diet. Additionally, research has indicated a connection
              between improved optimism and self-esteem and having a restful
              night's sleep.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-3">
              Developing your personal brand is beneficial as well. When you
              present a favorable picture of who you really are, you'll probably
              start getting the compliments that are crucial for your
              self-esteem.
            </p>
          </div>
          <li class="mx-10 mb-2">Review Past Achievements</li>
          <div class="mx-10 mb-5 font-normal text-sm">
            <p class="mb-2">
              Being able to declare, "I can do this, and here's the evidence,"
              will boost your confidence. Based on your prior successes, you
              will have determined what areas of your Personal SWOT Analysis you
              are strong in.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-3">
              Put your top ten accomplishments in a "achievement log." Next,
              make affirmations about your abilities using them. These quotes
              have extra impact if you have a tendency to use negative self-talk
              to erode your confidence.
            </p>
          </div>
          <li class="mx-10 mb-2">Set Confidence-Boosting Goals</li>
          <div class="mx-10 mb-5 font-normal text-sm">
            <p class="mb-2">
              Developing your self-confidence can be facilitated by setting and
              completing goals, as well as by evaluating your progress. Make
              goals that maximize your possibilities, minimize your weaknesses,
              and play to your strengths by using your personal SWOT analysis.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-3">
              Once you've determined the main objectives you wish to accomplish,
              make a list of the necessary first steps. Make sure they are
              manageable and shouldn't take more than an hour to complete. This
              will set things in motion and boost your self-esteem as you
              accomplish sensible objectives.
            </p>
          </div>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </article>

